        "The electrical circuit is broken",
        "Current cannot return to the transformer",
        "No fault current can flow",
        "The loop is incomplete"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP2",
        "TP5"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider what is needed for any electrical current to flow from a source and back again."
    },
    {
      "title": "Internal Path Components (R1 and R2)",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What code letter is used to represent the resistance of the line conductor in the earth loop?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "R1"
          ],
          "hint": "This is the 'outward' path to the fault.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the technical name for the conductor represented by the code letter R2?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Circuit Protective Conductor",
            "CPC"
          ],
          "hint": "This is the internal return path from the fault.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP3"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which specific conductor carries the fault current from the consumer unit to the point of the fault?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Line conductor",
            "R1"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the 'outward' part of the internal wiring.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is the internal part of the loop (R1 + R2) the section that an electrician has the most direct control over during installation?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "The electrician selects the cable sizes",
        "The electrician installs the wiring",
        "The electrician ensures tight connections",
        "It is the part inside the building"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP5"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about who is responsible for the wiring inside the consumer's property."
    },
    {
      "title": "External Path Components (Ze)",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What code letter represents the impedance of the loop that is external to the building?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Ze"
          ],
          "hint": "The 'e' stands for external.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the full name of the central junction point where the internal earth conductors connect to the supplier's path?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Main Earthing Terminal",
            "MET"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the 'hub' of the earthing system.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the final leg of the journey that carries current from the MET back to the transformer?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Supplier earth return path"
          ],
          "hint": "This is often the metal sheath of the service cable.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP3"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "If an installation has a very low (R1 + R2) but the supplier's earth return path is damaged, why is the circuit still considered unsafe?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "The total impedance will be too high",
        "Ze is part of the total path",
        "Fault current cannot return to the source efficiently",
        "The protective device will not trip"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP5"
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that the total path is the sum of both internal and external parts."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Total Path (Zs)",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What code letter represents the total earth loop impedance of the entire path?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Zs"
          ],
          "hint": "This is the sum of the internal and external parts.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "In the formula Zs = Ze + (R1 + R2), what does the 'Ze' represent?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "External earth loop impedance",
            "External impedance"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the part of the loop outside the installation.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "In the physical sequence of the fault loop, which component does the current enter immediately after leaving the CPC (R2)?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Main Earthing Terminal",
            "MET"
          ],
          "hint": "It is the junction point where all earths meet before leaving the building.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP3"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does knowing the full sequence of the earth loop path help an electrician diagnose a high Zs reading on a circuit?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Allows them to check individual components",
        "Helps identify if the fault is internal or external",
        "Can isolate if the issue is R1, R2, or Ze",
        "Pinpoints high resistance connections"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP3",
        "TP5"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about how breaking the path down into its constituent parts makes troubleshooting easier."
    }
  ]
}

