    "objective": "Synthesize the full path of a fault current from the point of contact back to the source, identifying the sequence of components and their relationship to the total impedance (Zs).",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "The earth loop is a continuous circuit from the source and back.",
      "Internal components: R1 (Line) and R2 (CPC).",
      "External components: Ze, MET, and the supplier's return path.",
      "Zs = Ze + (R1 + R2)."
    ],
    "questionText": "A fault occurs when the line conductor (R1) touches the metal casing of a heater. Trace the journey of the fault current from that metal casing all the way back to the supply transformer. In your description, name the specific components the current passes through in the correct sequence and explain how these parts are mathematically combined to find the total earth loop impedance (Zs).",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The current travels from the metal casing through the Circuit Protective Conductor (R2) to the Main Earthing Terminal (MET).",
      "From the MET, the current travels through the supplier earth return path to reach the transformer.",
      "The total earth loop impedance (Zs) is calculated by adding the external impedance (Ze) to the sum of the internal resistances (R1 + R2).",
      "Sequence: R2 -> MET -> Supplier earth return path -> Transformer."
    ],
    "hint": "Start your journey at the appliance's earth wire (R2), pass through the central junction point in the building, and follow the supplier's cable back to the source. Don't forget to mention the Zs formula!"
  }
}

